title: It's not a flag ship type of phone, but it's close and fantastic for the price!
text: I've heard good things about BLU phones, but never could bring myself to buy one until recently.  My wife's Motorola Droid Force 2 started acting up and I figured it was time to bite the bullet and get another phone.  I tried to get her another Motorola, but made the mistake of getting her a G6 Play model.  Not a wise choice.  She got frustrated with the performance issues quickly, so I looked on Amazon for an inexpensive alternative.  I found this phone.  The specs were what I was looking for.  Got the phone despite some bad reviews, and I couldn't be happier.  My wife LOVES the phone.  The pre-installed screen protector was a nice touch, and the cases, although flimsy, work well enough.  My wife really likes the  artsy one.  What I really liked was that the phone was EXTREMELY easy to set up.  After the initial set up, my Unreal Mobile SIM card was inserted, and APN settings were auto configured for me.  I rebooted the phone and it set up was complete.  Took me all of five minutes, if that,  to get the phone ready for use.  Lastly, the phone is very responsive.  There is no discernible lag when moving between screens or using multiple apps.  We don't play graphically intense games on the phone, but normal games run well. I am very impressed with this phone and will be looking to purchase either this same phone or another BLU phone in the future.

text:

2. If you travel around the country much, you're probably going to notice a difference in coverage. Mint may not work for your needs. I'd read the reviews to make sure Mint is right for you.
3. If you're not a heavy data user, don't leave a strong Tmobile covered area much and are interested in saving some $$$ per month, then try this out. It's worth it.

title: DOESN'T STAY ON DASH IF EVER REMOVED
text:
UPDATE -- This piece of crap has the same problem all of these dash mounts seem to have. They work FINE as long as you never remove them from the dash once you've placed them there. But if they're ever removed, the suction cup never works again.

I had my car serviced last week, and for some reason, the mechanics took this off my dash. I put it back on, and it fell off the next day even though it was holding nothing. I'm glad my iPhone wasn't attached to it.

I spent more money to get this one because I thought with all the adjustment buttons and the base plate it would work better than the cheaper one I had had. It didn't.

I'm going to super glue it to the dash. It's either that or go into debt for a newer car with GPS, and since I drive less than 20 miles per month, that doesn't seem necessary. (Agoraphobia has it's advantages. :-D )

ORIGINAL REVIEW -- This is a very nice phone mount. It comes with clear instructions that are actually presented verbally and not just graphically, which is rare in our increasingly illiterate culture. I wish the arm that extends the phone were longer. I live in Las Vegas, and even though my dashboard is light beige, the sun and heat are so intense in the summer that my iPhone doesn't work at all if it's placed anywhere near the window. title: Another Product With Decreasing Value
text: As an American consumer, I'm sick of corporations that produce an ideal product and then begin cutting features to increase profits. I've been using these styluses for over a year, and they are high quality. However, when I purchased mine, they DID include an ink barrel, which according to the answer to a question above, they no longer do. That's nothing. A change that HAS decreased the value of this product is that replacement fiber tips were available because those do show wear over time and stop being effective. Those replacement tips are no longer available anywhere as far as I can determine. Now we get to either deal with mushy, ineffective tips or buy a completely new stylus. No, the styluses aren't that expensive. It is simply a matter of a corporation's attitude toward consumers that is objectionable. Perhaps instead of cutting services and decreasing the value of products, corporations could consider having fewer do-nothing executives or paying them less. (As a former corporate executive, I know what they spend their time doing, which is going to useless meetings so no one has to take responsibility for decisions or actions.) American consumers should not be the least important consideration for corporations, and we are. Yes, this is still a good stylus. But I'm much more likely to try another brand or go without because this corporation has demonstrated a lack of interest in consumer needs.

title: Too many faults, not functional for me!
text:
I've installed more screen protectors than I'd like to count; therefore, I consider myself pretty capable.

First impression: I do not like the black border around the protector, I prefer it to be clear. The snap on guide seems useless and to be a complete waste of time and resources. I question the “warranty” - I'm not comfortable simply emailing a gmail account to validate a lifetime warranty. I suspect doing so would open up Pandora's box of phishing schemes and bulk junk emails. Why not just validate the alleged warranty from Amazon purchases? And what exactly IS the warranty? Inside the packaging, there is nothing to explain what is and isn't covered and how the program works. Is there a shipping fee? Does the “warranty” only provide a future purchase at a discount rate?

My verdict: Bubbles, Bubbles, BUBBLES!

I followed the instructions to the letter and my result was horrible.

I “wasted” my first screen using the snap on screen tool. By using this “tool,” the protector adhered incorrectly over the front facing camera and sensor.

I removed that screen, tossed it along with the snap on guide and was then able to correctly line up the protector.

Screen #2 better aligned but bubbles galore. Both edges are a hot mess.

The protector distorts my screen color. Extremely distracting.

My facial recognition sensor now no longer functions instantly. It's delayed and rendered inefficient.

Screen touch is SLOOOW. I'm having to long press each key multiple times just to type.

Without yet placing my case over my phone, I tested voice recording. The sound is muffled.

The protector does not feel sturdy enough to even protect.

I'm going to cut my losses, use this while waiting 2 more days for Prime to deliver a protector from another vendor. Once that protector arrives, I'll remove this brand and toss it.

Your review and results may differ. I'm personally not going to allow a $13 product to intrude upon how I expect my $1200 phone to function.

I dropped my phone twice and both times the tempered glass cracked.  I am disappointed because the case is very aesthetically appealing to the eye, with it's sleek design and fun color palette, but not after using it for more than one day.  Also, I recently purchased a Belkin charging dock, and it would not charge on the dock with the case on, which should have been no problem, with the removable bottom piece.  Except for when I took that off, there is the soft inner liner that also prevented the connection, so I had to take that off too.  Too much trouble to do every time I want to dock it.  I hope to see a future product with a liner built into each piece of the case, for easy docking, as well as a tougher outer casing so every bump doesn't damage the case and take the paint off.

title: Gives the "rapidly charging" message for all models of Google Pixel phones
text: One of the few Quick Charge 4.0 devices out there.  I wanted QC 4.0 so it could fast-charge any device I plugged in, but primarily my Google Pixel 3 XL phone (via USB-C to USB-C cable) and also a first generation iPad Pro (via USB-C to Lightning cable). Both scenarios work great. It's one of the few ways to get that "rapidly charging" on the Pixel since that depends on Power Delivery (PD), which is covered by QC 4.0 but not on most other chargers that call themselves "fast."

title: You Had -ONE- Job!
text:
I REALLY wanted this to work. I find the charging port on my Galaxy S5 to be really cumbersome, and I hate going to bed with that slight frustration and irritation that comes from fumbling with the charging cable. So this wireless charger seemed like a GREAT idea - I could just set the phone down on this thing and go to sleep!

At first it seemed like it worked. I had properly installed the charger piece in the phone and when I set the phone on the charger, the green light lit up at the bottom and the phone announced that it was now charging - MAGIC!

That same night, I kept waking up because my phone's screen kept waking up (lighting up the room) throughout the night for some reason. That's when I discovered that this charger will charge for a few minutes, and then stop suddenly (solid green light turns to a red blinking light for a few seconds and then solid red). Then, a few minutes later, the red light will go off, and the phone will start charging again... for a few minutes, and the whole cycle just repeats over and over and over again.

Ultimately, the phone never really gets charged if I have any apps that run in the background (e.g. CNN) and Bluetooth/Wifi turned on because everything together sucks more juice than the little spurts of power that come from the few minutes of charging. So the result is a dead, warm phone in the morning (unless I disable everything, which sort of defeats the convenience aspect of this product).

Just to be sure it wasn't a bad power issue, I tried this charger on another outlet / circuit and got the same result. Then I plugged it into my UPS unit (which regulates voltage) and still got the same result. I also tried removing the phone from its Otterbox case (just in case the intermittent issue was something related to the case), and again, same result.

I came here to leave a review and discovered that several other people were having the same issue, and that TYLT had responded, asking them to email customer service to see about a replacement. So before I wrote this review, I emailed TYLT and explained the issue. That was 4 business days ago, and I haven't even gotten an auto-reply to confirm they received my email. So not only does my TYLT charger not work, their customer service apparently doesn't respond to emails.

I guess I will be returning this and staying away from TYLT products in the future. Maybe there's another charger that will work better...

title: Only works with extended battery without the battery's cover, weak kickstand
text:
Wondering why some reviewers say that it doesn't fit the extended battery and others say it works beautifully? Keep reading - I'll explain.

Based on another review, it sounded like this case would work with the Hyperion extended battery, so I bought both and got them today.

The Hyperion extended battery comes with the battery itself and the "extended" back for the phone which curves around to allow space for the larger battery. It looked great by itself, so I then started to put on the Seidio case.

The Seidio case comes with a rubber-like skin that wraps around the phone, and then a harder "skeleton" case that goes around the rubber.

For about 5 solid minutes, I tried to fit the phone into that case without any luck. The curved Hyperion battery back introduces a curve over the camera lens and flash area, but the hard Seidio case is designed to "push" into that area, so it pushes against the battery back and it just won't fit.

The only way to make it fit is to actually LEAVE OFF the battery backing for the Hyperion battery. Once you do that, it fits decently well, and it covers the entire backside of the phone, so the battery case isn't needed. I honestly do not like this one bit. I would much prefer to have both the Hyperion battery cover AND the Seidio case on at the same time. I hate having "leftover" parts for things that I just bought. I knocked off two stars off my rating just for this design - I would have never bought this case if I had known this.

So if you read other conflicting reviews, you'll be able to tell who tried to fit the Seidio case around everything versus the people who left off the battery backing.

I'm okay with the feel of the case. The buttons are accessible, no ports are blocked or anything, and I don't feel as concerned about the phone falling out of my pocket.

I don't like the kickstand because it BARELY works. It will fold under the slightest pressure. So if a cable is connected, you're only going to be able to use the kickstand in one orientation. If they had simply designed it to be slightly thicker and with a slight curve at the end (a la HTC Thunderbolt), it would have made it a hundred times more versatile.

Don't buy this for the kickstand, and don't buy this if you want to keep your battery case cover on. Otherwise, go for it.
